{"title_page": "Naledi Pandor", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use South African English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name             = Naledi Pandor\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image            = Minister N Pandor - TWAS (2010) (cropped).jpg\n|caption          = Pandor in 2010\n<!-- -->\n|office           = [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n|deputy           = [[Alvin Botes]]<br />[[Candith Mashego-Dlamini]]\n|term_start       = 30 May 2019\n|term_end         = \n|president        = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor      = [[Lindiwe Sisulu]]\n<!-- -->\n|office1          = [[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]]\n| deputy1         = [[Buti Manamela]]\n|term_start1      = 27 February 2018\n|term_end1        = 29 May 2019\n|president1       = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor1     = [[Hlengiwe Mkhize]]\n|successor1       = ''Ministry split''\n<!-- -->\n|office2          = [[Department of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]\n|deputy2          = [[Zanele kaMagwaza-Msibi]]\n|president2       = [[Jacob Zuma]]<br />[[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|term_start2      = 26 May 2014\n|term_end2        = 26 February 2018\n|predecessor2     = [[Derek Hanekom]]\n|successor2       = [[Nkhensani Kubayi-Ngubane]]\n|president3       = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|deputy3          = [[Zanele kaMagwaza-Msibi]]\n|term_start3      = 10 May 2009\n|term_end3        = 4 October 2012\n|predecessor3     = [[Mosibudi Mangena]]\n|successor3       = [[Derek Hanekom]]\n<!-- -->\n|office4          = [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n|deputy4          = [[Fatima Chohan]]\n|president4       = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|term_start4      = 4 October 2012\n|term_end4        = 25 May 2014<br /><small>[[Acting (law)|Acting]]: 2 \u2013 4 October 2012</small>\n|predecessor4     = [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]\n|successor4       = [[Malusi Gigaba]]\n<!-- -->\n|office5          = [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]\n|deputy5          = [[Enver Surty]]\n|president5       = [[Thabo Mbeki]]<br />[[Kgalema Motlanthe]]\n|term_start5      = 12 May 2004\n|term_end5        = 10 May 2009\n|predecessor5     = [[Kader Asmal]]\n|successor5       = ''Ministry split''\n<!-- -->\n|office6          = [[President of the Senate of South Africa|Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces]]\n|president6       = [[Thabo Mbeki]]\n|term_start6      = 21 June 1999\n|term_end6        = 4 May 2004\n|predecessor6     = [[Mosiuoa Lekota]]\n|successor6       = [[Joyce Kgoali]]\n<!-- -->\n|birth_name       = Grace Naledi Mandisa Matthews\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|12|7}}\n|birth_place      = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province]], [[Union of South Africa]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|alma_mater       = {{Flatlist|\n* [[University of Botswana]]\n* [[University of Swaziland]]\n* [[University of London]]\n* [[Kennedy School of Government]]\n* [[Stellenbosch University]]\n* [[University of Pretoria]]\n}}\n|party            = [[African National Congress]]\n|relations        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Z. K. Matthews]] (grandfather)\n* [[Joe Matthews (politician)|Joe Matthews]] (father)\n}}\n|spouse           = Sharif Joseph Pandor\n|children         = 4\n|residence        = \n|occupation       = \n|signature        = \n|website          = \n|footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor''' (n\u00e9e '''Matthews'''; born 7 December 1953) is a South African academic, educationist, lecturer and politician serving as the [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] since 2019. She has served as a [[Parliament of South Africa|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) since 1994.\n\nBorn in [[Durban]], Pandor completed high school in [[Botswana]]. She qualified as a teacher and taught at multiple schools and universities, whilst she achieved various degrees from different universities.<ref name=\"Ministers\">{{cite news |title=Ministers |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2005-12-01-ministers |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=1 December 2005 |archiveurl=https://mg.co.za/article/2005-12-01-ministers |archivedate=10 November 2019}}</ref> Pandor took office as a Member of Parliament in 1994.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She soon became Deputy Chief Whip of the ANC caucus in 1995.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She was elected Deputy Chairperson of the [[National Council of Provinces]] in 1998 and became Chairperson in 1999.<ref name=\"Ministers\" />\n\nShe initially became a member of the national cabinet in 2004, following President [[Thabo Mbeki]]'s decision to appoint her as [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet Mbeki's 'delivery' team |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/meet-mbekis-delivery-team-211708 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=29 April 2004}}</ref> She retained her post in the cabinet of [[Kgalema Motlanthe]]. Newly-elected President [[Jacob Zuma]] named her [[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jacob Zuma announces cabinet choices |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/jacob-zuma-announces-cabinet-choices |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=10 May 2009}}</ref> She served in the position until her appointment as [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cabinet reshuffle on cards |url=https://www.iol.co.za/the-star/soweto/cabinet-reshuffle-on-cards-1396039 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=4 October 2012}}</ref> She returned to the post of Minister of Science and Technology in 2014 and held it until 2018, when she became [[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]] in the [[First Cabinet of Cyril Ramaphosa|first cabinet of President Cyril Ramaphosa]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicolson |first1=Greg |title=Who\u2019s Who of the Zuma\u2019s new Cabinet |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-05-26-whos-who-of-the-zumas-new-cabinet/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunter |first1=Qaanitah |title=Ramaphosa swings the axe, cuts 13 from Zuma's Cabinet |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-02-26-ramaphosa-swings-the-axe-cuts-14-from-zumas-cabinet/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2019 general election, Pandor was mentioned as a possible candidate for [[Deputy President of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Calls mount for SA to appoint female deputy president |url=https://www.enca.com/news/sa-speculates-who-could-be-second |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=23 May 2019}}</ref> She was instead appointed Minister of International Relations and Cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Du Plessis |first1=Carien |title=Diplomats hail Naledi Pandor\u2019s new International Relations job |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-05-31-diplomats-hail-naledi-pandors-new-international-relations-job/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGrace Naledi Mandisa Matthews was born on 7 December 1953 in [[Durban]], [[Natal Province|Natal]] to Regina Thelma (died 2002) and [[Joe Matthews (politician)|Joe Matthews]] (1929\u20132010), a political and anti-apartheid activist and the son of black academic [[Z. K. Matthews]] (1901\u20131968).<ref>{{cite news |title=Former deputy minister Joe Matthews dies |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2010-08-19-former-deputy-minister-joe-matthews-dies |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=19 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Minister Naledi Pandor\u2019s father, Joe Matthews, dies |url=https://www.gov.za/minister-naledi-pandor%E2%80%99s-father-joe-matthews-dies |website=South African Government |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref> She received her primary and secondary education in [[Botswana]]. She matriculated from Gaborone Secondary School. Between 1973 and 1977, she achieved a Certificate for Continuing Education and bachelor's degree from the [[University of Swaziland]] and the [[University of Botswana]], respectively.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She proceeded to head overseas and fulfilled a Diploma in Education and an MA degree from the [[University of London]] between 1978 and 1979.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /><ref name=\"timeslive1604\">{{cite news |title=Higher education's Naledi Pandor caps string of qualifications with doctorate |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-04-16-higher-educations-naledi-pandor-caps-string-of-qualifications-with-doctorate/ |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nPandor obtained a Diploma in Higher Education, Administration and Leadership from the Bryn Mawr Summer Programme in 1992, and soon enrolled at the [[Kennedy School of Government]] to receive a Diploma in Leadership in Development in 1997. She also attained an MA degree in Linguistics from the [[University of Stellenbosch]] in the same year.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> Pandor received her PhD in Education at the [[University of Pretoria]] in 2019, with a thesis titled \"The contested meaning of transformation in higher education in post-apartheid South Africa\".<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Petersen |first1=Tammy |title=Minister Pandor walks the walk, graduating with PhD in Education |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/minister-pandor-walks-the-walk-graduating-with-phd-in-education-20190416 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LOOK: 'She continues to inspire us': Naledi Pandor awarded PhD |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/look-she-continues-to-inspire-us-naledi-pandor-awarded-phd-21444274 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=16 April 2019 |location=Pretoria, Gauteng}}</ref>\n\n==Teaching career==\nPandor became a teacher at the Ernest Bevin School in [[London]] in 1980. She was soon employed as a teacher in [[Gaborone]] in 1981 and worked as one until 1984. She proceeded to serve as an instructor at the Taung College of Education from 1984 to 1986. Pandor worked as a senior lecturer in English at the [[University of Bophuthatswana]] from 1986 to 1989. She soon worked as a senior fellow in the Academic Support Programme of the [[University of Cape Town]] between 1989 and 1994.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nWhile at the University of Bophuthatswana, Pandor served as the chair of the university's Union of Democratic Staff Associations between 1988 and 1990. She was appointed the chairperson of the Western Cape National Executive Committee of the National Education Coordinating Committee in 1991 and served in the position until 1993. At the same time, she was part of the ANC's Western Cape Education Committee.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nAdditionally, Pandor chaired the ANC Athlone Central branch, whilst serving as both the head of the Desmond Tutu Education Trust and the Western Cape School Building Trust.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nFrom 1992 to 1995, she worked as deputy head of the Tertiary Education Fund of South Africa. She soon became head of the fund. She was also deputy chairperson of the Joint Education Trust Board of Trustees between 1993 and 2001.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nShe was chancellor of Cape Technikon from 2002 to 2004. During the same period, she was a member of the governing council of the [[University of Fort Hare]].<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n[[File:Naledi Pandor 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Pandor at the opening exhibition of the German-South African Science Year in Cape Town in 2012]]\nPandor became a Member of the Parliament in the lower house of Parliament, the [[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]], following the [[1994 South African general election|1994 general election]].<ref name=\"encaex\">{{cite news |title=EXPLAINER: Who is Naledi Pandor? |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/who-is-naledi-pandor |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=6 November 2017}}</ref> Within the ANC caucus, she served as Deputy Chief Whip from 1995 until her deployment to the upper house of Parliament, the [[National Council of Provinces]], in 1998. She served as Deputy Chairperson until her appointment as Chairperson following the [[1999 South African general election|1999 general election]]. She succeeded inaugural Chairperson [[Mosioua Lekota]] when she assumed the office on 21 June 1999. She was the first woman to hold the role. [[Joyce Kgoali]] succeeded Pandor in 2004 and consequently became the second woman to hold the role.<ref name=\"encaex\" />\n\nPandor returned to the National Assembly following the [[2004 South African general election|2004 general election]]. President [[Thabo Mbeki]] appointed her to the role of [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]. She took office on 12 May 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mbeki's cabinet list |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Mbekis-cabinet-list-20040428 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=28 April 2004}}</ref> During her tenure in the portfolio, she was responsible for a complete overhaul of the nation's education system. Pandor initiated reforms to the country's failed implementation of the [[outcomes-based education]] (OBE) system.<ref>{{cite news |title=Own-language schooling, for free |url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/governance/education/curriculum-180505 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Brand South Africa |date=18 May 2005}}</ref> Mbeki resigned in 2008 and left [[Kgalema Motlanthe]] in charge. Motlanthe retained Pandor in her position in his interim cabinet.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Motlanthe sworn in as interim president |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2008-09-25-motlanthe-sworn-in-as-interim-president |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=25 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=President Motlanthe\u2019s new cabinet |url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/governance/developmentnews/cabinet260908 |website=Brand South Africa |accessdate=24 September 2019|date=26 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Harsh Vardhan with the Vice Minister for Science, Technology and Innovation of Brazil, Mr. \u00c1lvaro Toubes Prata, the Deputy Minister of Federation of Russia, Mr. Alexey Lopatia (1).jpg|thumb|Pandor and her ministerial counterparts at the 4th BRICS Science & Technology Ministers Meeting in 2016]]\nFollowing the [[2009 South African general election|2009 general election]], Jacob Zuma became the new President of South Africa. He unbundled the Education Ministry into two new portfolios and appointed Pandor to the newly-established post of [[Minister of Science and Technology]] in May 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rossouw |first1=Mandy |title=Zuma's Cabinet: Those who didn't make the cut |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-10-zumas-cabinet-those-who-didnt-make-the-cut |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=10 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=South Africa Cabinet Members 2009 to 2010 |url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/article/south-africa-cabinet-members-2009-2010 |website=South African History Online |accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> During her time in the position, Pandor served as a driving force for South Africa to host the [[Square Kilometre Array]] (SKA) in the Karoo region. South Africa won the bid.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tshivhidzo |first1=Edwin |title=SA will win bid to host SKA - Pandor |url=https://www.sanews.gov.za/south-africa/sa-will-win-bid-host-ska-pandor |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=SA News |date=31 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Richard |title=South Africa eyes SKA telescope with bated breath |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-02-15-south-africa-eyes-ska-telescope-with-bated-breath |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=15 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=President Zuma congratulates Minister of Science and Technology on winning the bid to host the SKA |url=https://www.gov.za/president-zuma-congratulates-minister-science-and-technology-winning-bid-host-ska |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=South African Government |date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]] resigned as [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in order for her to take up the role as [[African Union|Chair of the African Union]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maasho |first1=Aaron |title=Dlamini-Zuma elected to head AU Commission |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-07-16-dlamini-zuma-elected-to-head-au-commission |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=16 July 2012}}</ref> Her resignation caused a vacancy in the cabinet. President Zuma consequently appointed Pandor as Minister of Home Affairs in an acting capacity on 2 October 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pandor appointed acting home affairs minister |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-10-02-pandor-appointed-acting-home-affairs-minister |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Soon after on 4 October 2012, Zuma formally appointed her as Minister of Home Affairs.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Maharaj |first1=Mac |title=Naledi Pandor appointed Home Affairs minister - Presidency |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/naledi-pandor-appointed-home-affairs-minister--pre |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=3 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her re-election in the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]], President Zuma announced that Pandor would return to the [[Department of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Department of Science and Technology]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Complete list of cabinet ministers |url=https://www.enca.com/elections-2014-information/president-jacob-zuma-announces-his-cabinet |accessdate=24 September 2014 |newspaper=eNCA |date=25 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zuma shakes things up with new Cabinet |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/zuma-shakes-things-new-cabinet |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=25 May 2014}}</ref> [[Malusi Gigaba]] succeeded her as Minister of Home Affairs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peyper |first1=Lindsey |title=Gigaba in hot seat as new Finance Minister |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/gigaba-in-hot-seat-as-new-finance-minister-20170331|newspaper=News24 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |date=31 March 2017}}</ref> She took office on 26 May 2014 and succeeded [[Derek Hanekom]].<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Quintal |first1=Genevieve |title=Marathon swearing-in for Zuma\u2019s Cabinet |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/marathon-swearing-in-for-zumas-cabinet-1694171 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zuma names new cabinet |url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2014-05-26-zuma-names-new-cabinet/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=SowetanLIVE |date=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Cyril Ramaphosa]] assumed the office of President in February 2018. Pandor was appointed [[Minister of Higher Education and Training]] and took office on 27 February 2018, succeeding [[Hlengiwe Mkhize]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rabkin |first1=Franny |last2=Pather |first2=Ra'eesa |title=New deputy president, finance minister announced in major Cabinet reshuffle |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-02-26-ramaphosa-cabinet-reshuffle-february-2018 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=26 February 2018 |quote=Minister of Higher education - Naledi Pandor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Who is in and who is out: Ramaphosa's Cabinet reshuffle |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/who-is-in-and-who-is-out-ramaphosas-cabinet-reshuffle-20180226 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=26 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=IN FULL Ramaphosa hires and fires - read his Cabinet reshuffle speech |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-02-26-in-full--ramaphosa-hires-and-fires-read-his-cabinet-reshuffle-speech/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general election]], the Ministry of Higher Education and Training was split. Pandor was speculated to be appointed [[Deputy President of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dlamini-Zuma, Pandor tipped to become deputy president |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/dlamini-zuma-pandor-tipped-to-become-deputy-president-20190522 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=22 May 2019}}</ref> She was President Ramaphosa's original choice for Deputy President back in 2017 at the [[54th National Conference of the African National Congress|ANC's elective conference]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicolson |first1=Greg |title=#ANCdecides2017: The Top Six that could have been |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-12-18-ancdecides2017-the-top-six-that-could-have-been/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=18 December 2017}}</ref> She was instead appointed [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] and assumed the post on 30 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Introducing the executives Cyril Ramaphosa has chosen to serve SA |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-30-the-men-and-women-cyril-ramaphosa-has-chosen-to-serve-sa/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=BusinessDay |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPandor is married to Sharif Joseph Pandor, whom she met while studying in [[Botswana]], and they have four children together, Fazlur, Aisha, Suraya and Haroon. She converted to [[Islam]] after she met her husband. Her in-laws gave her the Islamic name of Nadia. On her religious conversion, Pandor said: \"My parents said God is God. As long as you worship Him we will support you and the Islamic principles are universal. Certainly, Islam demands much more of you in terms of observance.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Humble and willing to learn: Naledi Pandor is leading by example |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-05-19-humble-and-willing-to-learn-naledi-pandor-is-leading-by-example/ |newspaper=The Sunday Times |accessdate=23 September 2019 |date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Naledi Pandor}}\n* {{People's Assembly (South Africa)|grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor|Naledi Pandor}}\n* [https://www.sahistory.org.za/people/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor \u2013 South African History Online]\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor-ms Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor, Ms \u2013 South African Government]\n* [http://www.dirco.gov.za/department/profile_pandor.html  Profile: Dr Naledi Pandor, Minister \u2013 Dirco]\n* [https://www.dst.gov.za/index.php/media-room/20-temp/organogram/218-naledi-pandor-biography Naledi Pandor Biographical notes \u2013 dst.gov.za]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lindiwe Sisulu]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hlengiwe Mkhize]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Ministry split''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Derek Hanekom]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nkhensani Kubayi-Ngubane]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Malusi Gigaba]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mosibudi Mangena]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]|years=2009\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Derek Hanekom]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kader Asmal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Ministry split''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mosiuoa Lekota]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Council of Provinces|Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces]]|years=1999\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joyce Kgoali]]}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{SouthAfricaSenateNCOPPresidents}}\n{{G20-Foreign}}\n{{Thabo Mbeki cabinet 2}}\n{{Kgalema Motlanthe cabinet 1}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 1}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandor, Naledi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Education ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Home Affairs of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Chairpersons of the National Council of Provinces]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Eswatini alumni]]\n[[Category:South African Muslims]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of South Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use South African English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name             = Naledi Pandor\n|honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n|image            = Minister N Pandor - TWAS (2010) (cropped).jpg\n|caption          = Pandor in 2010\n<!-- -->\n|office           = [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n|deputy           = [[Alvin Botes]]<br />[[Candith Mashego-Dlamini]]\n|term_start       = 30 May 2019\n|term_end         = \n|president        = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor      = [[Lindiwe Sisulu]]\n<!-- -->\n|office1          = [[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]]\n| deputy1         = [[Buti Manamela]]\n|term_start1      = 27 February 2018\n|term_end1        = 29 May 2019\n|president1       = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|predecessor1     = [[Hlengiwe Mkhize]]\n|successor1       = ''Ministry split''\n<!-- -->\n|office2          = [[Department of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]\n|deputy2          = [[Zanele kaMagwaza-Msibi]]\n|president2       = [[Jacob Zuma]]<br />[[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n|term_start2      = 26 May 2014\n|term_end2        = 26 February 2018\n|predecessor2     = [[Derek Hanekom]]\n|successor2       = [[Nkhensani Kubayi-Ngubane]]\n|president3       = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|deputy3          = [[Zanele kaMagwaza-Msibi]]\n|term_start3      = 10 May 2009\n|term_end3        = 4 October 2012\n|predecessor3     = [[Mosibudi Mangena]]\n|successor3       = [[Derek Hanekom]]\n<!-- -->\n|office4          = [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n|deputy4          = [[Fatima Chohan]]\n|president4       = [[Jacob Zuma]]\n|term_start4      = 4 October 2012\n|term_end4        = 25 May 2014<br /><small>[[Acting (law)|Acting]]: 2 \u2013 4 October 2012</small>\n|predecessor4     = [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]\n|successor4       = [[Malusi Gigaba]]\n<!-- -->\n|office5          = [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]\n|deputy5          = [[Enver Surty]]\n|president5       = [[Thabo Mbeki]]<br />[[Kgalema Motlanthe]]\n|term_start5      = 12 May 2004\n|term_end5        = 10 May 2009\n|predecessor5     = [[Kader Asmal]]\n|successor5       = ''Ministry split''\n<!-- -->\n|office6          = [[President of the Senate of South Africa|Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces]]\n|president6       = [[Thabo Mbeki]]\n|term_start6      = 21 June 1999\n|term_end6        = 4 May 2004\n|predecessor6     = [[Mosiuoa Lekota]]\n|successor6       = [[Joyce Kgoali]]\n<!-- -->\n|birth_name       = Grace Naledi Mandisa Matthews\n|birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|12|7}}\n|birth_place      = [[Durban]], [[Natal Province]], [[Union of South Africa]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|alma_mater       = {{Flatlist|\n* [[University of Botswana]]\n* [[University of Swaziland]]\n* [[University of London]]\n* [[Kennedy School of Government]]\n* [[Stellenbosch University]]\n* [[University of Pretoria]]\n}}\n|party            = [[African National Congress]]\n|relations        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Z. K. Matthews]] (grandfather)\n* [[Joe Matthews (politician)|Joe Matthews]] (father)\n}}\n|spouse           = Sharif Joseph Pandor\n|children         = 4\n|residence        = \n|occupation       = \n|signature        = \n|website          = \n|footnotes        = \n}}\n\n'''Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor''' (n\u00e9e '''Matthews'''; born 7 December 1953) is a South African academic, educationist, lecturer and politician serving as the [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] since 2019. She has served as a [[Parliament of South Africa|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for the [[African National Congress]] (ANC) since 1994.\n\nBorn in [[Durban]], Pandor completed high school in [[Botswana]]. She qualified as a teacher and taught at multiple schools and universities, whilst she achieved various degrees from different universities.<ref name=\"Ministers\">{{cite news |title=Ministers |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2005-12-01-ministers |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=1 December 2005 |archiveurl=https://mg.co.za/article/2005-12-01-ministers |archivedate=10 November 2019}}</ref> Pandor took office as a Member of Parliament in 1994.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She soon became Deputy Chief Whip of the ANC caucus in 1995.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She was elected Deputy Chairperson of the [[National Council of Provinces]] in 1998 and became Chairperson in 1999.<ref name=\"Ministers\" />\n\nShe initially became a member of the national cabinet in 2004, following President [[Thabo Mbeki]]'s decision to appoint her as [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Meet Mbeki's 'delivery' team |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/meet-mbekis-delivery-team-211708 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=29 April 2004}}</ref> She retained her post in the cabinet of [[Kgalema Motlanthe]]. Newly-elected President [[Jacob Zuma]] named her [[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=Jacob Zuma announces cabinet choices |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/news-and-analysis/jacob-zuma-announces-cabinet-choices |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=10 May 2009}}</ref> She served in the position until her appointment as [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cabinet reshuffle on cards |url=https://www.iol.co.za/the-star/soweto/cabinet-reshuffle-on-cards-1396039 |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=4 October 2012}}</ref> She returned to the post of Minister of Science and Technology in 2014 and held it until 2018, when she became [[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]] in the [[First Cabinet of Cyril Ramaphosa|first cabinet of President Cyril Ramaphosa]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicolson |first1=Greg |title=Who\u2019s Who of the Zuma\u2019s new Cabinet |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2014-05-26-whos-who-of-the-zumas-new-cabinet/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunter |first1=Qaanitah |title=Ramaphosa swings the axe, cuts 13 from Zuma's Cabinet |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-02-26-ramaphosa-swings-the-axe-cuts-14-from-zumas-cabinet/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2019 general election, Pandor was mentioned as a possible candidate for [[Deputy President of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Calls mount for SA to appoint female deputy president |url=https://www.enca.com/news/sa-speculates-who-could-be-second |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=23 May 2019}}</ref> She was instead appointed Minister of International Relations and Cooperation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Du Plessis |first1=Carien |title=Diplomats hail Naledi Pandor\u2019s new International Relations job |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2019-05-31-diplomats-hail-naledi-pandors-new-international-relations-job/ |accessdate=10 November 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGrace Naledi Mandisa Matthews was born on 7 December 1953 in [[Durban]], [[Natal Province|Natal]] to Regina Thelma (died 2002) and [[Joe Matthews (politician)|Joe Matthews]] (1929\u20132010), a political and anti-apartheid activist and the son of black academic [[Z. K. Matthews]] (1901\u20131968).<ref>{{cite news |title=Former deputy minister Joe Matthews dies |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2010-08-19-former-deputy-minister-joe-matthews-dies |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=19 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Minister Naledi Pandor\u2019s father, Joe Matthews, dies |url=https://www.gov.za/minister-naledi-pandor%E2%80%99s-father-joe-matthews-dies |website=South African Government |accessdate=23 September 2019}}</ref> She received her primary and secondary education in [[Botswana]]. She matriculated from Gaborone Secondary School. Between 1973 and 1977, she achieved a Certificate for Continuing Education and bachelor's degree from the [[University of Swaziland]] and the [[University of Botswana]], respectively.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> She proceeded to head overseas and fulfilled a Diploma in Education and an MA degree from the [[University of London]] between 1978 and 1979.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /><ref name=\"timeslive1604\">{{cite news |title=Higher education's Naledi Pandor caps string of qualifications with doctorate |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-04-16-higher-educations-naledi-pandor-caps-string-of-qualifications-with-doctorate/ |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nPandor obtained a Diploma in Higher Education, Administration and Leadership from Bryn Mawr Summer Programme in 1992, and soon enrolled at the [[Kennedy School of Government]] to receive a Diploma in Leadership in Development in 1997. She also attained an MA degree in Linguistics from the [[University of Stellenbosch]] in the same year.<ref name=\"Ministers\" /> Pandor received her PhD in Education at the [[University of Pretoria]] in 2019, with a thesis titled \"The contested meaning of transformation in higher education in post-apartheid South Africa\".<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Petersen |first1=Tammy |title=Minister Pandor walks the walk, graduating with PhD in Education |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/minister-pandor-walks-the-walk-graduating-with-phd-in-education-20190416 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=16 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LOOK: 'She continues to inspire us': Naledi Pandor awarded PhD |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/look-she-continues-to-inspire-us-naledi-pandor-awarded-phd-21444274 |accessdate=23 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=16 April 2019 |location=Pretoria, Gauteng}}</ref>\n\n==Teaching career==\nPandor became a teacher at the Ernest Bevin School in [[London]] in 1980. She was soon employed as a teacher in [[Gaborone]] in 1981 and worked as one until 1984. She proceeded to serve as an instructor at the Taung College of Education from 1984 to 1986. Pandor worked as a senior lecturer in English at the [[University of Bophuthatswana]] from 1986 to 1989. She soon worked as a senior fellow in the Academic Support Programme of the [[University of Cape Town]] between 1989 and 1994.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nWhile at the University of Bophuthatswana, Pandor served as the chair of the university's Union of Democratic Staff Associations between 1988 and 1990. She was appointed the chairperson of the Western Cape National Executive Committee of the National Education Coordinating Committee in 1991 and served in the position until 1993. At the same time, she was part of the ANC's Western Cape Education Committee.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nAdditionally, Pandor chaired the ANC Athlone Central branch, whilst serving as both the head of the Desmond Tutu Education Trust and the Western Cape School Building Trust.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nFrom 1992 to 1995, she worked as deputy head of the Tertiary Education Fund of South Africa. She soon became head of the fund. She was also deputy chairperson of the Joint Education Trust Board of Trustees between 1993 and 2001.<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\nShe was chancellor of Cape Technikon from 2002 to 2004. During the same period, she was a member of the governing council of the [[University of Fort Hare]].<ref name=\"timeslive1604\" />\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n[[File:Naledi Pandor 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Pandor at the opening exhibition of the German-South African Science Year in Cape Town in 2012]]\nPandor became a Member of the Parliament in the lower house of Parliament, the [[National Assembly of South Africa|National Assembly]], following the [[1994 South African general election|1994 general election]].<ref name=\"encaex\">{{cite news |title=EXPLAINER: Who is Naledi Pandor? |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/who-is-naledi-pandor |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=6 November 2017}}</ref> Within the ANC caucus, she served as Deputy Chief Whip from 1995 until her deployment to the upper house of Parliament, the [[National Council of Provinces]], in 1998. She served as Deputy Chairperson until her appointment as Chairperson following the [[1999 South African general election|1999 general election]]. She succeeded inaugural Chairperson [[Mosioua Lekota]] when she assumed the office on 21 June 1999. She was the first woman to hold the role. [[Joyce Kgoali]] succeeded Pandor in 2004 and consequently became the second woman to hold the role.<ref name=\"encaex\" />\n\nPandor returned to the National Assembly following the [[2004 South African general election|2004 general election]]. President [[Thabo Mbeki]] appointed her to the role of [[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]. She took office on 12 May 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mbeki's cabinet list |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Mbekis-cabinet-list-20040428 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=28 April 2004}}</ref> During her tenure in the portfolio, she was responsible for a complete overhaul of the nation's education system. Pandor initiated reforms to the country's failed implementation of the [[outcomes-based education]] (OBE) system.<ref>{{cite news |title=Own-language schooling, for free |url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/governance/education/curriculum-180505 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Brand South Africa |date=18 May 2005}}</ref> Mbeki resigned in 2008 and left [[Kgalema Motlanthe]] in charge. Motlanthe retained Pandor in her position in his interim cabinet.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Motlanthe sworn in as interim president |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2008-09-25-motlanthe-sworn-in-as-interim-president |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=25 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=President Motlanthe\u2019s new cabinet |url=https://www.brandsouthafrica.com/governance/developmentnews/cabinet260908 |website=Brand South Africa |accessdate=24 September 2019|date=26 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Harsh Vardhan with the Vice Minister for Science, Technology and Innovation of Brazil, Mr. \u00c1lvaro Toubes Prata, the Deputy Minister of Federation of Russia, Mr. Alexey Lopatia (1).jpg|thumb|Pandor and her ministerial counterparts at the 4th BRICS Science & Technology Ministers Meeting in 2016]]\nFollowing the [[2009 South African general election|2009 general election]], Jacob Zuma became the new President of South Africa. He unbundled the Education Ministry into two new portfolios and appointed Pandor to the newly-established post of [[Minister of Science and Technology]] in May 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rossouw |first1=Mandy |title=Zuma's Cabinet: Those who didn't make the cut |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2009-05-10-zumas-cabinet-those-who-didnt-make-the-cut |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=10 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=South Africa Cabinet Members 2009 to 2010 |url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/article/south-africa-cabinet-members-2009-2010 |website=South African History Online |accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref> During her time in the position, Pandor served as a driving force for South Africa to host the [[Square Kilometre Array]] (SKA) in the Karoo region. South Africa won the bid.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Tshivhidzo |first1=Edwin |title=SA will win bid to host SKA - Pandor |url=https://www.sanews.gov.za/south-africa/sa-will-win-bid-host-ska-pandor |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=SA News |date=31 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Davies |first1=Richard |title=South Africa eyes SKA telescope with bated breath |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-02-15-south-africa-eyes-ska-telescope-with-bated-breath |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=15 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=President Zuma congratulates Minister of Science and Technology on winning the bid to host the SKA |url=https://www.gov.za/president-zuma-congratulates-minister-science-and-technology-winning-bid-host-ska |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=South African Government |date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, [[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]] resigned as [[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in order for her to take up the role as [[African Union|Chair of the African Union]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maasho |first1=Aaron |title=Dlamini-Zuma elected to head AU Commission |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-07-16-dlamini-zuma-elected-to-head-au-commission |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=16 July 2012}}</ref> Her resignation caused a vacancy in the cabinet. President Zuma consequently appointed Pandor as Minister of Home Affairs in an acting capacity on 2 October 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pandor appointed acting home affairs minister |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-10-02-pandor-appointed-acting-home-affairs-minister |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Soon after on 4 October 2012, Zuma formally appointed her as Minister of Home Affairs.<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Maharaj |first1=Mac |title=Naledi Pandor appointed Home Affairs minister - Presidency |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/naledi-pandor-appointed-home-affairs-minister--pre |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=3 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing her re-election in the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]], President Zuma announced that Pandor would return to the [[Department of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Department of Science and Technology]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Complete list of cabinet ministers |url=https://www.enca.com/elections-2014-information/president-jacob-zuma-announces-his-cabinet |accessdate=24 September 2014 |newspaper=eNCA |date=25 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zuma shakes things up with new Cabinet |url=https://www.enca.com/south-africa/zuma-shakes-things-new-cabinet |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=eNCA |date=25 May 2014}}</ref> [[Malusi Gigaba]] succeeded her as Minister of Home Affairs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peyper |first1=Lindsey |title=Gigaba in hot seat as new Finance Minister |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/gigaba-in-hot-seat-as-new-finance-minister-20170331|newspaper=News24 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |date=31 March 2017}}</ref> She took office on 26 May 2014 and succeeded [[Derek Hanekom]].<ref name=\"encaex\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Quintal |first1=Genevieve |title=Marathon swearing-in for Zuma\u2019s Cabinet |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/marathon-swearing-in-for-zumas-cabinet-1694171 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=IOL |date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zuma names new cabinet |url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/2014-05-26-zuma-names-new-cabinet/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=SowetanLIVE |date=26 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Cyril Ramaphosa]] assumed the office of President in February 2018. Pandor was appointed [[Minister of Higher Education and Training]] and took office on 27 February 2018, succeeding [[Hlengiwe Mkhize]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rabkin |first1=Franny |last2=Pather |first2=Ra'eesa |title=New deputy president, finance minister announced in major Cabinet reshuffle |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2018-02-26-ramaphosa-cabinet-reshuffle-february-2018 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=26 February 2018 |quote=Minister of Higher education - Naledi Pandor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Who is in and who is out: Ramaphosa's Cabinet reshuffle |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/who-is-in-and-who-is-out-ramaphosas-cabinet-reshuffle-20180226 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=26 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=IN FULL Ramaphosa hires and fires - read his Cabinet reshuffle speech |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2018-02-26-in-full--ramaphosa-hires-and-fires-read-his-cabinet-reshuffle-speech/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=26 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[2019 South African general election|2019 general election]], the Ministry of Higher Education and Training was split. Pandor was speculated to be appointed [[Deputy President of South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Dlamini-Zuma, Pandor tipped to become deputy president |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/dlamini-zuma-pandor-tipped-to-become-deputy-president-20190522 |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=News24 |date=22 May 2019}}</ref> She was President Ramaphosa's original choice for Deputy President back in 2017 at the [[54th National Conference of the African National Congress|ANC's elective conference]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nicolson |first1=Greg |title=#ANCdecides2017: The Top Six that could have been |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2017-12-18-ancdecides2017-the-top-six-that-could-have-been/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=18 December 2017}}</ref> She was instead appointed [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] and assumed the post on 30 May 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Introducing the executives Cyril Ramaphosa has chosen to serve SA |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2019-05-30-the-men-and-women-cyril-ramaphosa-has-chosen-to-serve-sa/ |accessdate=24 September 2019 |newspaper=BusinessDay |date=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPandor is married to Sharif Joseph Pandor, whom she met while studying in [[Botswana]], and they have four children together, Fazlur, Aisha, Suraya and Haroon. She converted to [[Islam]] after she met her husband. Her in-laws gave her the Islamic name of Nadia. On her religious conversion, Pandor said: \"My parents said God is God. As long as you worship Him we will support you and the Islamic principles are universal. Certainly, Islam demands much more of you in terms of observance.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Humble and willing to learn: Naledi Pandor is leading by example |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/news/2019-05-19-humble-and-willing-to-learn-naledi-pandor-is-leading-by-example/ |newspaper=The Sunday Times |accessdate=23 September 2019 |date=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Naledi Pandor}}\n* {{People's Assembly (South Africa)|grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor|Naledi Pandor}}\n* [https://www.sahistory.org.za/people/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor \u2013 South African History Online]\n* [https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/grace-naledi-mandisa-pandor-ms Grace Naledi Mandisa Pandor, Ms \u2013 South African Government]\n* [http://www.dirco.gov.za/department/profile_pandor.html  Profile: Dr Naledi Pandor, Minister \u2013 Dirco]\n* [https://www.dst.gov.za/index.php/media-room/20-temp/organogram/218-naledi-pandor-biography Naledi Pandor Biographical notes \u2013 dst.gov.za]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Lindiwe Sisulu]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title= [[Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hlengiwe Mkhize]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Higher Education and Training (South Africa)|Minister of Higher Education and Training]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Ministry split''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Derek Hanekom]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nkhensani Kubayi-Ngubane]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (South Africa)|Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Malusi Gigaba]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mosibudi Mangena]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Science and Technology (South Africa)|Minister of Science and Technology]]|years=2009\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Derek Hanekom]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kader Asmal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Education (South Africa)|Minister of Education]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Ministry split''}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mosiuoa Lekota]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Council of Provinces|Chairperson of the National Council of Provinces]]|years=1999\u20132004}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joyce Kgoali]]}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n{{SouthAfricaSenateNCOPPresidents}}\n{{G20-Foreign}}\n{{Thabo Mbeki cabinet 2}}\n{{Kgalema Motlanthe cabinet 1}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 1}}\n{{Jacob Zuma cabinet 2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandor, Naledi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Education ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Home Affairs of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Chairpersons of the National Council of Provinces]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Eswatini alumni]]\n[[Category:South African Muslims]]\n[[Category:Converts to Islam]]\n[[Category:People from Durban]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Foreign ministers of South Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:The", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naledi_Pandor"}
{"title_page": "Lam Pin Min", "text_new": "{{Chinese name|[[Lan (surname \u84dd)|Lam]]}}\nDr '''Lam Pin Min''' ({{zh|s=\u84dd\u5f6c\u660e|zh|t=\u85cd\u5f6c\u660e|p=L\u00e1n B\u012bnm\u00edng}}; born 1 September 1969) is a [[politician]] and [[Physician|medical doctor]] from [[Singapore]]. A member of the country's governing [[People's Action Party]] (PAP), he is currently a [[Senior Minister of State#Minor government ranks|Senior Minister of State]] in the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] and the [[Ministry of Transport (Singapore)|Ministry of Transport]]. He has been a [[Parliament of Singapore|Member of Parliament]] (MP) since 2006.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gov.sg/docs/default-source/default-document-library/cv-dr-lam-pin-min-for-parliament.pdf|title=Dr Lam Pin Min|last=|first=|date=|website=Singapore Parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/about-us/senior-management/sms-dr-lam-pin-min_jul-2017.pdf|title=Dr Lam Pin Min|last=|first=|date=July 2017|website=Ministry of Health Singapore|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is a Chinese Singaporean of [[Hakka people|Hakka]] descent<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anne-nguyen.blogspot.com/2008/10/lam-pin-min.html|title=Hakka people: Lam Pin Min|last=Jodaidro|date=2008-10-11|website=Hakka people|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Category:Singaporean people of Hakka descent|date=2018-06-02|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Category:Singaporean_people_of_Hakka_descent&oldid=844072613|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> from the Lam clan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LamPinMin/posts/3022305247799431|title=Lam Pin Min\uff08\u84dd\u5f6c\u660e\uff09|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>, and has family roots in [[Dabu County]], [[Guangdong]], [[China]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Category:People from Dabu|date=2015-07-30|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Category:People_from_Dabu&oldid=673732140|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life ==\nLam has four siblings - two brothers and a younger sister.\u00a0As the middle child, he is quoted to have had to \"recycle the secondhand textbooks handed down from [his] elder brother.\" He grew up in one of the earliest [[Housing and Development Board|HDB]] flats in Tanglin Halt Road. It was a 3-room HDB flat \u2013 2 bedrooms and 1 living room, with only one bedroom being air-conditioned. The house\u00a0was cramped and the siblings had to sleep on mattresses on the floor. Lam's father was the sole breadwinner as his mother stayed home to look after the four children.\u00a0All three of his siblings, and him, have graduated from university, supported by their parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031192632/http://lampinmin.sg/2011/03/29/reminiscing-the-past-2/|title=Lam Pin Min - Reminiscing the Past|date=2016-10-31|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Lam claims he grew up wanting to be a veterinarian, but his parents thought that studying to become a doctor locally would be much cheaper.\n\n==Career==\nLam served as a regular medical officer in the [[Singapore Armed Forces|Singapore Armed Forces (SAF)]] in 1995, obtaining a Diploma in Aviation Medicine from the [[United Kingdom]] in 1997 and subsequently a [[Fellow|Fellowship]] in the [[Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh|Royal College of Surgeons (Edinburgh]]) and a Master in [[Ophthalmology|Medicine in Ophthalmology]] from the [[National University of Singapore|National University of Singapore (NUS)]] in 2000. Dr Lam held many appointments in the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force|Republic of Singapore Air Force (RSAF)]], including Officer Commanding in an Airbase Medical Centre and as a Branch Head in the RSAF Aeromedical Centre. He also spent 3 months serving as the medical commander of the Singapore Medical Contingent, serving in the [[United Nations]] Military Hospital in [[East Timor]] during pre-independence in 2000.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://mustsharenews.com/lam-pin-min-facts/|title=8 Lam Pin Min Facts That Help You Understand The Minister At The Heart Of The PMD Saga|last=Yee|first=Jonathan|date=2019-11-16|website=Must Share News - Independent News For Singaporeans|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enewsletter.ntu.edu.sg/thelkcmedicine/Issue19/Pages/In-Focus-Humanity-In-Medicine.aspx?AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=Humanity in Medicine|website=enewsletter.ntu.edu.sg|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Lam was trained as an [[Aviation medicine|Aviation Medicine]] Specialist and served the RSAF as a medical officer and [[Flight surgeon|Flight Surgeon]] from 1995 to 2003, before moving into clinical practice in 2003. Prior to becoming a Minister of State, he served as a [[Pediatric ophthalmology|pediatric ophthalmologist]] at [[KK Women's and Children's Hospital]],the [[Singapore National Eye Centre]], and Eagle Eye Centre.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Public-Figure/LamPinMin/about/|title=Lam Pin Min\uff08\u84dd\u5f6c\u660e\uff09|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medicalhub.com.sg/doctor/eagle-eye-centre/|title=Eagle Eye Centre|website=Medical Hub|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Lam sits on the Civil Aviation Medical Board and is the Adviser to the Society of Aviation Medicine, Singapore.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Political career===\nLam was first elected to parliament at the [[2006 Singaporean general election|2006 general election]] as a member of the PAP team in the [[Ang Mo Kio Group Representation Constituency]]. He was part of the six-member PAP team (led by [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]]) which defeated the team from the [[Workers' Party of Singapore|Workers' Party]] by 96,636 votes (66.1%) to 49,479 (33.9%).\n\nAt the [[2011 Singaporean general election|2011 general election]], Lam's [[Sengkang West Single Member Constituency|Sengkang West]] ward (which encompasses [[Anchorvale]] and [[Fernvale, Singapore|Fernvale]] of [[Sengkang New Town]]) was made a single-member constituency. Lam stood in the single-member constituency and defeated Koh Choong Yong of the Workers' Party by 14,689 votes (58.1%) to 10,591 (41.9%).\n\nAt the [[2015 Singaporean general election|2015 general election]], Lam defeated Koh Choong Yong of the Worker's Party in Sengkang West SMC after scoring 62.1% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/ge2015-lam-pin-min-wins-sengkang-west-smc|title=GE2015: Lam Pin Min wins Sengkang West SMC|last=Lim|first=Royston|date=2015-09-12|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nLam served as the Chairman of the Government Parliamentary Committee for Health from 2009 to 2014 (having previously been the Deputy Chairman from 2006 to 2008).<ref>[https://www.moh.gov.sg/content/dam/moh_web/About%20Us/Dr%20Lam%20Pin%20Min.pdf Dr Lam Pin Min, Minister of State]. Ministry of Health website, retrieved 8 September 2015.</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Lam was appointed a Minister of State in the Ministry of Health.<ref>[http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/incumbent-lam-pin-min/2051184.html Incumbent Lam Pin Min will defend Sengkang West SMC]. Channel NewsAsia, 15 August 2015.</ref>\n\nSubsequently in May 2017, Dr Lam was appointed Senior Minister of State in the Ministry of Health and the Ministry of Transport.<ref>[http://www.pmo.gov.sg/newsroom/changes-cabinet-and-other-appointments-0#annex_a]. PMO website</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn January 2015, Lam was involved in a controversy wherein [[Build to order (HDB)|Build-To-Order]] residents in Fernvale Lea, in his Sengkang West ward, were not informed of plans to build a [[columbarium]] next to their block.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/how-the-columbarium-saga-unfolded|title=How the columbarium saga unfolded|last=Hio|first=Lester|date=2015-01-30|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> During a meeting with residents, Dr Lam was spotted sitting alongside the contractors, leading to a misunderstanding that he was on their side instead of the residents\u2019. Minister for National Development [[Khaw Boon Wan]] informed Parliament that there will be no commercial columbarium at the site.\n\nIn February 2018 it was revealed that Lam had sent an appeal letter directly to [[State Courts of Singapore|State Courts]] to help his resident, Tang Ling Lee, who was sentenced to one week jail for seriously injuring a motorcyclist in a road traffic accident. The High Court Judge, justice [[See Kee Oon]] dismissed the appeal, stating that Lam's letter had misrepresented the facts and trivialised the injuries sustained by the rider. This incident led to a furor online with many [[Netizen|netizens]] questioning why Lam, a legislative as well as an executive member of the government, was overstepping his duty by interfering with the judiciary.<ref>https://www.theonlinecitizen.com/2018/02/06/retired-judge-counters-chan-with-lkys-instruction-not-to-write-appeal-letters-to-courts/</ref> Such letters should be forwarded to the Attorney-General\u2019s Chambers first.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Education==\nLam was educated in [[Anglo-Chinese School|Anglo-Chinese School (ACS)]] and [[National Junior College|National Junior College (NJC)]]. He graduated from Medical School, [[National University of Singapore|National University of Singapore (NUS)]] in 1993. He then joined the Singapore Armed Forces (SAF) as a regular medical officer in 1995. Whilst in service in the [[Singapore Armed Forces|Singapore Armed Forces (SAF)]], he obtained his postgraduate Diploma in Aviation Medicine from the [[Royal College of Physicians|Royal College of Physicians (London)]] in 1997 and subsequently a Fellowship in the [[Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh|Royal College of Surgeons (Edinburgh)]] and a Master in Medicine in Ophthalmology from NUS in 2000.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhgei-ioc.com.sg/guest-honour|title=Guest of Honour {{!}} International Ophthalmology Congress|website=www.nhgei-ioc.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLam is married and has two daughters.<ref name=\":2\" /> He is a [[Christianity|Christian]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LamPinMin/posts/3300831559946797|title=Lam Pin Min\uff08\u84dd\u5f6c\u660e\uff09|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Category:Singaporean Christians|date=2019-01-06|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Category:Singaporean_Christians&oldid=877143862|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lampinmin.sg/ lampinmin.sg] (now defunct)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161007175936/http://lampinmin.sg/ Archive] of lampinmin.sg\n* [http://www.parliament.gov.sg/mp/lam-pin-min?viewcv=Lam%20Pin%20Min Lam Pin Min] at the Parliament of Singapore website\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par | sg}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl | title    = Member of Parliament <br /> for [[Ang Mo Kio GRC]] (Sengkang West)\n        | years    = 2006 \u2013 2011}}\n{{s-non | reason   = Constituency redrawn}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl | title    = Member of Parliament <br /> for [[Sengkang West SMC]]\n        | years    = 2011 \u2013 present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Singapore MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lam, Pin Min}}\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Singapore]]\n[[Category:People's Action Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Singaporean ophthalmologists]]\n[[Category:National University of Singapore alumni]]\n[[Category:National Junior College alumni]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Chinese School alumni]]\n[[Category:Singaporean people of Hakka descent]]\n[[Category:People from Dabu]]\n[[Category:Singaporean Christians]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese name|[[Lan (surname \u84dd)|Lam]]}}\nDr '''Lam Pin Min''' ({{zh|s=\u84dd\u5f6c\u660e|zh|t=\u85cd\u5f6c\u660e|p=L\u00e1n B\u012bnm\u00edng}}; born 1 September 1969) is a [[politician]] and [[Physician|medical doctor]] from [[Singapore]]. A member of the country's governing [[People's Action Party]] (PAP), he is currently a [[Senior Minister of State#Minor government ranks|Senior Minister of State]] in the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] and the [[Ministry of Transport (Singapore)|Ministry of Transport]]. He has been a [[Parliament of Singapore|Member of Parliament]] (MP) since 2006.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.parliament.gov.sg/docs/default-source/default-document-library/cv-dr-lam-pin-min-for-parliament.pdf|title=Dr Lam Pin Min|last=|first=|date=|website=Singapore Parliament|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/about-us/senior-management/sms-dr-lam-pin-min_jul-2017.pdf|title=Dr Lam Pin Min|last=|first=|date=July 2017|website=Ministry of Health Singapore|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is a Chinese Singaporean of [[Hakka people|Hakka]] descent<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anne-nguyen.blogspot.com/2008/10/lam-pin-min.html|title=Hakka people: Lam Pin Min|last=Jodaidro|date=2008-10-11|website=Hakka people|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Category:Singaporean people of Hakka descent|date=2018-06-02|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Category:Singaporean_people_of_Hakka_descent&oldid=844072613|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> from the Lam clan<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LamPinMin/posts/3022305247799431|title=Lam Pin Min\uff08\u84dd\u5f6c\u660e\uff09|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>, and has family roots in [[Dabu County]], [[Guangdong]], [[China]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Category:People from Dabu|date=2015-07-30|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Category:People_from_Dabu&oldid=673732140|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Early Life ==\nLam has four siblings - two brothers and a younger sister.\u00a0As the middle child, he is quoted to have had to \"recycle the secondhand textbooks handed down from [his] elder brother.\" He grew up in one of the earliest [[Housing and Development Board|HDB]] flats in Tanglin Halt Road. It was a 3-room HDB flat \u2013 2 bedrooms and 1 living room, with only one bedroom being air-conditioned. The house\u00a0was cramped and the siblings had to sleep on mattresses on the floor. Lam's father was the sole breadwinner as his mother stayed home to look after the four children.\u00a0All three of his siblings, and him, have graduated from university, supported by their parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031192632/http://lampinmin.sg/2011/03/29/reminiscing-the-past-2/|title=Lam Pin Min - Reminiscing the Past|date=2016-10-31|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Lam claims he grew up wanting to be a veterinarian, but his parents thought that studying to become a doctor locally would be much cheaper.\n\n==Career==\nLam served as a regular medical officer in the [[Singapore Armed Forces|Singapore Armed Forces (SAF)]] in 1995, obtaining a Diploma in Aviation Medicine from the [[United Kingdom]] in 1997 and subsequently a [[Fellow|Fellowship]] in the [[Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh|Royal College of Surgeons (Edinburgh]]) and a Master in [[Ophthalmology|Medicine in Ophthalmology]] from the [[National University of Singapore|National University of Singapore (NUS)]] in 2000. Dr Lam held many appointments in the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force|Republic of Singapore Air Force (RSAF)]], including Officer Commanding in an Airbase Medical Centre and as a Branch Head in the RSAF Aeromedical Centre. He also spent 3 months serving as the medical commander of the Singapore Medical Contingent, serving in the [[United Nations]] Military Hospital in [[East Timor]] during pre-independence in 2000.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://mustsharenews.com/lam-pin-min-facts/|title=8 Lam Pin Min Facts That Help You Understand The Minister At The Heart Of The PMD Saga|last=Yee|first=Jonathan|date=2019-11-16|website=Must Share News - Independent News For Singaporeans|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enewsletter.ntu.edu.sg/thelkcmedicine/Issue19/Pages/In-Focus-Humanity-In-Medicine.aspx?AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=Humanity in Medicine|website=enewsletter.ntu.edu.sg|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Lam was trained as an [[Aviation medicine|Aviation Medicine]] Specialist and served the RSAF as a medical officer and [[Flight surgeon|Flight Surgeon]] from 1995 to 2003, before moving into clinical practice in 2003. Prior to becoming a Minister of State, he served as a [[Pediatric ophthalmology|pediatric ophthalmologist]] at [[KK Women's and Children's Hospital]],the [[Singapore National Eye Centre]], and Eagle Eye Centre.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Public-Figure/LamPinMin/about/|title=Lam Pin Min\uff08\u84dd\u5f6c\u660e\uff09|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medicalhub.com.sg/doctor/eagle-eye-centre/|title=Eagle Eye Centre|website=Medical Hub|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Lam sits on the Civil Aviation Medical Board and is the Adviser to the Society of Aviation Medicine, Singapore.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Political career===\nLam was first elected to parliament at the [[2006 Singaporean general election|2006 general election]] as a member of the PAP team in the [[Ang Mo Kio Group Representation Constituency]]. He was part of the six-member PAP team (led by [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]]) which defeated the team from the [[Workers' Party of Singapore|Workers' Party]] by 96,636 votes (66.1%) to 49,479 (33.9%).\n\nAt the [[2011 Singaporean general election|2011 general election]], Lam's [[Sengkang West Single Member Constituency|Sengkang West]] ward (which encompasses [[Anchorvale]] and [[Fernvale, Singapore|Fernvale]] of [[Sengkang New Town]]) was made a single-member constituency. Lam stood in the single-member constituency and defeated Koh Choong Yong of the Workers' Party by 14,689 votes (58.1%) to 10,591 (41.9%).\n\nAt the [[2015 Singaporean general election|2015 general election]], Lam defeated Koh Choong Yong of the Worker's Party in Sengkang West SMC after scoring 62.1% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/ge2015-lam-pin-min-wins-sengkang-west-smc|title=GE2015: Lam Pin Min wins Sengkang West SMC|last=Lim|first=Royston|date=2015-09-12|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nLam served as the Chairman of the Government Parliamentary Committee for Health from 2009 to 2014 (having previously been the Deputy Chairman from 2006 to 2008).<ref>[https://www.moh.gov.sg/content/dam/moh_web/About%20Us/Dr%20Lam%20Pin%20Min.pdf Dr Lam Pin Min, Minister of State]. Ministry of Health website, retrieved 8 September 2015.</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Lam was appointed a Minister of State in the Ministry of Health.<ref>[http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/incumbent-lam-pin-min/2051184.html Incumbent Lam Pin Min will defend Sengkang West SMC]. Channel NewsAsia, 15 August 2015.</ref>\n\nSubsequently in May 2017, Dr Lam was appointed Senior Minister of State in the Ministry of Health and the Ministry of Transport.<ref>[http://www.pmo.gov.sg/newsroom/changes-cabinet-and-other-appointments-0#annex_a]. PMO website</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn January 2015, Lam was involved in a controversy wherein [[Build to order (HDB)|Build-To-Order]] residents in Fernvale Lea, in his Sengkang West ward, were not informed of plans to build a [[columbarium]] next to their block.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/housing/how-the-columbarium-saga-unfolded|title=How the columbarium saga unfolded|last=Hio|first=Lester|date=2015-01-30|website=The Straits Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> During a meeting with residents, Dr Lam was spotted sitting alongside the contractors, leading to a misunderstanding that he was on their side instead of the residents\u2019. Minister for National Development [[Khaw Boon Wan]] informed Parliament that there will be no commercial columbarium at the site.\n\nIn February 2018 it was revealed that Lam had sent an appeal letter directly to [[State Courts of Singapore|State Courts]] to help his resident, Tang Ling Lee, who was sentenced to one week jail for seriously injuring a motorcyclist in a road traffic accident. The High Court Judge, justice [[See Kee Oon]] dismissed the appeal, stating that Lam's letter had misrepresented the facts and trivialised the injuries sustained by the rider. This incident led to a furor online with many [[Netizen|netizens]] questioning why Lam, a legislative as well as an executive member of the government, was overstepping his duty by interfering with the judiciary.<ref>https://www.theonlinecitizen.com/2018/02/06/retired-judge-counters-chan-with-lkys-instruction-not-to-write-appeal-letters-to-courts/</ref> Such letters should be forwarded to the Attorney-General\u2019s Chambers first.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Education==\nLam was educated in [[Anglo-Chinese School|Anglo-Chinese School (ACS)]] and [[National Junior College|National Junior College (NJC)]]. He graduated from Medical School, [[National University of Singapore|National University of Singapore (NUS)]] in 1993. He then joined the Singapore Armed Forces (SAF) as a regular medical officer in 1995. Whilst in service in the [[Singapore Armed Forces|Singapore Armed Forces (SAF)]], he obtained his postgraduate Diploma in Aviation Medicine from the [[Royal College of Physicians|Royal College of Physicians (London)]] in 1997 and subsequently a Fellowship in the [[Royal College of Surgeons of Edinburgh|Royal College of Surgeons (Edinburgh)]] and a Master in Medicine in Ophthalmology from NUS in 2000.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhgei-ioc.com.sg/guest-honour|title=Guest of Honour {{!}} International Ophthalmology Congress|website=www.nhgei-ioc.com.sg|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLam is married and has two daughters.<ref name=\":2\" /> He is of the [[Christianity|Christian]] faith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LamPinMin/posts/3300831559946797|title=Lam Pin Min\uff08\u84dd\u5f6c\u660e\uff09|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Category:Singaporean Christians|date=2019-01-06|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Category:Singaporean_Christians&oldid=877143862|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://lampinmin.sg/ lampinmin.sg] (now defunct)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20161007175936/http://lampinmin.sg/ Archive] of lampinmin.sg\n* [http://www.parliament.gov.sg/mp/lam-pin-min?viewcv=Lam%20Pin%20Min Lam Pin Min] at the Parliament of Singapore website\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par | sg}}\n{{s-new | constituency}}\n{{s-ttl | title    = Member of Parliament <br /> for [[Ang Mo Kio GRC]] (Sengkang West)\n        | years 